display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex> that has a final object <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[e]]></fr:tex> and finite sums.
    For <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  Y_\bullet \to  X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, the cone <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C(u)]]></fr:tex> satisfies
    <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[       C(u)_n       = X_n{\,\textstyle \coprod \,}\coprod _{i<n} Y_i{\,\textstyle \coprod \,}e.     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p><fr:p>We take <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex> to be:

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        the category of topological spaces and continuous maps, with final object <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[e=P^t]]></fr:tex>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        the category of pairs <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,F)]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a topological space and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> is an abelian sheaf on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, with an arrow <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(u,f)\colon (Y,F)\to (X,G)]]></fr:tex> consisting of a continuous map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  Y\to  X]]></fr:tex> and a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>-morphism (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.5"
href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.5.xml"
number="5.1.5" />) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  G\to  F]]></fr:tex>, with final object <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[e=(P^t,0)]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
