display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> (respectively), and let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  K\to  L]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>-morphism.
    We thus obtain a complex <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C(f)]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C(u)]]></fr:tex>.
    We again define the hypercohomology
    <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^n(C(u),C(f))       = \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^n(X_\bullet \operatorname {mod} Y_\bullet , K\operatorname {mod} L).     ]]></fr:tex>
    
